An interesting aspect of modern Catholic literature is that there is a tendency to see the ‘twin sisters’ of mercy and justice. Some writers say ‘they go together’. No advocate of justice will realize his plans without calm reflection on the human strivings and aspirations softly and modestly to advance, so far as possible, the right of human person. Anyone who moves wholly in this direction and another sooner or later becomes disappointed; he knows that mercy and justice never move together hand in hand. Here it is necessary to remedy the broken fellowship of justice and mercy in order to make two in one, in fact to carry them side by side in a greater solidarity and harmony. A duty to secure justice often stands in the way of a commitment to instructing love, and this requires that followers of Christ must become more independent. In one sentence we can say that the ideal of combining justice and mercy is no less than the Beatitudes (Maurach, 2006).
